references: Our ablation study in this subsection is to explore the best epoch number and learning rate for training HSJP pretext task. We try 3 different learning rates (3e-4, 1e-3, and 2e-3) as well as 3 different epoch numbers (120, 240, and 480) for our HSJP pretext task on HRNet W32, and their performances are reported in Table 2. When training HSJP pretext task for 120 epochs, the network cannot learn rich enough representations, and the downstream task cannot reach its best performance. When training 480 epochs, the precision on HSJP pretext is higher than that of 240 epochs, but it does not help to increase the mAP of downstream task: 2D human pose estimation. We finally select 240 as the number of epochs for training our HSJP pretext task, as it‚Äôs not only of high performance but also time-saving (Training for 480 epochs is time-consuming, but useless for downstream task). Table 3(a) illustrate that the pre-task can converge quickly at learning rate of 1e-3, and the network does not collapse. Thus we select 1e-3 as our learning rate.

references: For this concern, we test different settings of NùëÅN for our HSJP pretext task with HRNet W32 in this subsection, and finetune networks pretrained with different NùëÅN on the downstream 2D pose estimator. The HSJP and downstream mAP performances on MS-COCO val2017 dataset are reported with the metrics in Section 3.5 and 4.2. As Table 4(a) shows, with the increment of NùëÅN, the mAP score for downstream 2D human pose estimator firstly increases, and then decreases. However, the HSJP precision decreases with the increment of NùëÅN, because the complexity of jigsaw puzzling problem also increases. When N=6ùëÅ6N=6, the convergence and the representation capability of pretext task are able to reach a balance: the pretraining process on HSJP pretext task does not collapse, and the network also learns high-quality representations for downstream 2D pose estimator (although it‚Äôs of low HSJP precision, our purpose is not to solve jigsaw puzzles more accurately, but to learn representations for downstream task). Therefore, we split our original input image of 224√ó224224224224\times 224 into 6√ó6666\times 6 image patches.

As Figure 3 demonstrates, we compare our performance of pretext (HSJP) and downstream (2D pose estimation) tasks under different settings: whether adding unshuffled image into input. Our experiments are also performed on HRNet W32. Unfortunately, although concatenating unshuffled image benefits the HSJP precision for pretext, it does not improve the performance of pose estimation downstream task: the mAP score is even worse than almost all weights pretrained without taking unshuffled images as inputs, and the performance is not better than training directly from scratch for 450 epochs. (In our scheme, the pretext HSJP task is trained for 240 epoch, the downstream task is trained for 210 epochs, so we try to train for 240+210=450 epochs from scratch for fair comparison.) Therefore, we do not concatenate the original image into input during HSJP pretraining, even if it seems to be reasonable.
